-- Northeast Wholesale Power Falls as Demand Drops Below Forecasts
-- B y   N a u r e e n   S .   M a l i k
-- 2013-03-27T21:02:26Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-03-27/northeast-wholesale-power-falls-as-demand-drops-below-forecasts.html
Wholesale electricity prices from
New York to  Maine  declined as demand dropped below forecasts
amid milder weather.  The temperature in Boston was 51 degrees Fahrenheit (11
Celsius) at 2:20 p.m. and New York City’s John F. Kennedy
airport was at 50 degrees, according to AccuWeather Inc. in
State College, Pennsylvania. The New England system operator had
forecast a high for the day of 45 degrees for Boston while the
New York grid manager factored in 49 for JFK.  New York City prices dropped $7.15, or 16 percent, to
$38.13 a megawatt-hour from 7 a.m. to 4 p.m. from yesterday’s
on-peak average, the least since Feb. 28, according to the  New
York Independent System Operator Inc.   Spot power  on the six-
state grid from  Connecticut  to Maine slid $8.62, or 18 percent,
to $38.53 a megawatt-hour from yesterday’s on-peak average, the
least since March 13, ISO New England Inc. data show.  “Demand is lower than expected due to temperatures today
coming in stronger than forecast,” said Brendyn Brooks-
Stocking, a Boston-based analyst with Genscape Inc., which
tracks real-time data on the electricity grid. “The trend this
week is moderately below seasonal temps shifting to seasonal as
the week goes on.”  The NYISO predicted  electricity usage  demand across New
York City would peak at 6,484 megawatts from 11 a.m. until noon.
Peak demand so far today reached 6,331 megawatts during at 11:55
a.m. Power consumption yesterday rose as high as 6,307 megawatts
for the hour ended at 5 p.m.  New England  New England  projected  demand to peak at 16,100 megawatts at
7:30 p.m., down from 16,189 during the same hour  yesterday .  Cash prices for natural gas, a fuel used to generate
electricity, fell across most Northeast hubs today. Gas
accounted for 49 percent of the generation in New England as of
2:32 p.m., data from the grid operator shows.  Algonquin City Gates gas, which includes delivery to
 Boston , fell 74.67 cents, or 14 percent, to $4.70 per million
British thermal units on the Intercontinental Exchange, the
lowest price since Jan. 29. Spot prices at Transco Zone 6 for
New York City dropped 4.38 cents, or 1 percent, to $4.2352, the
fourth decline in five days.  On-peak power also fell across regions from the mid-
Atlantic states to Texas and California, while the Midwest
posted a slight gain.  Power prices for the PJM Interconnection LLC grid running
from New Jersey into North Carolina and  Illinois  gave up earlier
gains and slid for the fourth day as temperatures rose to the
high 40s and low 50s.  PJM Benchmark  On-peak electricity at PJM’s benchmark Western Hub, which
includes prices from  Pennsylvania  to  Washington , fell $3.47, or
8.2 percent, to average $38.68 until 4 p.m. from yesterday’s
average, the least since March 15.  Prices had jumped on higher-than-expected power use. PJM
 projected  peak demand of 100,228 megawatts at 7:30 a.m. Actual
usage at that time was 1.2 percent higher at 101,358. Demand
yesterday peaked at 103,979 megawatts at 7:25 a.m.  Power on the main Texas grid operated by the  Electric
Reliability Council of Texas Inc.  dropped for a second day.
Prices averaged $25.74 a megawatt-hour until 3 p.m. local time,
down $3.33, or 11 percent, from yesterday’s on-peak average.  Electricity at Southern California’s  SP15 hub  fell $17.48,
or 36 percent, to $30.68 a megawatt-hour for on-peak hours so
far today from yesterday, the least since March 16, according to
the  California Independent System Operator Corp.  Northern
 California ’s  NP15 hub  dropped $5.25, or 15 percent, to $30.91 a
megawatt-hour from yesterday, the third straight decline.  Power at the  Indiana hub , a benchmark for the Midwest,
slipped 38.4 cents, or 1.2 percent, from yesterday to $32.29 a
megawatt-hour from as of 2 p.m. versus yesterday’s on-peak
average, according to the Midwest Independent Transmission
System Operator Inc.  To contact the reporter on this story:
